ral version for use when the events are not necessarily independent. We will first present the version of rule 5 that is restricted to independent events, and in the next module we will revisit Rule 5 and present the more general version.","position":{"start":{"line":168,"column":1},"end":{"line":168,"column":1}},"key":"PW4XXzG6xf"}],"key":"PsNTBdZ6Mt"}],"key":"Ke2LaQeR1q"}],"key":"mlAh9CUC4X"},"references":{"cite":{"order":[],"data":{}}},"footer":{"navigation":{"prev":{"title":"Probability Rules (4 of 11)","url":"/pages/m09-probability-rules-4-of-11","group":"Unit 4: Probability"},"next":{"title":"Probability Rules (6 of 11)","url":"/pages/m09-probability-rules-6-of-11","group":"Unit 4: Probability"}}},"domain":"http://localhost:3001"}